<DOC><DOCNO> AP880405-0070 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0718EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Jews     04-05 0163</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Soviet-Jews,0168</SECOND><HEAD>Jewish Emigration At Seven-Year High In March</HEAD><DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Soviet authorities allowed 944 Jews to emigratelast month, the highest monthly figure since July 1981, aresettlement agency said today.   It was the second straight monthly increase in emigration, theIntergovernmental Committee for Migration reported. The agency said723 Jews left the Soviet Union in February and 658 emigrated inJanuary.   Last year, 8,011 Jews were allowed to leave the Soviet Union,the highest number since 1981. There were only 943 such emigres in1986.   In March, 176 of the Soviet Jews arriving at a transit center inVienna, Austria, went to Israel, agency spokeswoman Regina Boucaultsaid.   Recent emigration has remained far below the resettlementprogram's peak in 1979, when 51,330 Jews were allowed to leave theSoviet Union.   More than 250,000 Jews have emigrated since the program began in1971. In the early years, most emigres went to Israel. Recently,most emigres have chosen to settle elsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>